			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Well, finally decided to find a specialist ranger place, so registered here. Here is my first post then:
<br />

<br />
Here are some LDON tips.
<br />

<br />
I've done 16 LDON, 10 successes, 6 "Failures".
<br />

<br />
2 "failures" were when a group member entered the Dungeon prematurely, Once because of a lag patch, and once because the person got agro from a brownie or something, didn't know where to go to zone to loose it, and thought 'Hey I'll just jump down the dungeon'. Never mind that they were the first folk person there and that CLR is still off getting a mana buff. So on both of these by the time the group was formed up and buffed we were 10 minutes or so down.
<br />

<br />
2 "failures" were on collection missions, getting that elusive last drop, with groups that overall were working OK, not brilliant, but well enough to work through the dungeon steadily. On one occasion we got the final drop from the mob we were fighting as the mission timed out, and so missed by about 15 seconds. On the other occasion, we were down one drop at time out, and it took a crazy number of mobs (20 or so!) to get the final one.
<br />

<br />
1 "failure" was when the group went sour because one member decided to change roles, without telling anyone, because they didn't like the way things were going, and so started pulling! With no warning or discussion! Now in fact, they had a valid point, the group wasn't working too well, but their response was disastrous.
<br />

<br />
The final "failure" I can't recall.
<br />

<br />
Now, first off, note I say "failure" in inverted commas. The reason for this is that every dungeon I've ever been in, I came out WAY ahead on XP, cash and loot, improved my knowledge of group tactics AND met some great folk. Even the sour group contained 4 people I'd happily go with again.  OK, so in some of them we just came away with consolation points only, or even with no points on 1 or 2 times, but so what? I really don't care about the leader board. As far as I'm concerned every dungeon I've done was a roaring success! Yipee!
<br />

<br />
Now don't get me wrong, its good to stay mission focused, but not to the extent of becoming blinkered about it, or causing offence to someone.
<br />

<br />
Secondly, most of these failures can be seen to have occurred at the organisational stage.
<br />

<br />
LDON groups need leadership. There just isn't time to run them by comittee. Every group I'm in, I try to make sure that everyone is clear about who is in charge. Of course, leadership is a tricky skill, not everyone has the life experience to do it well, the fact that you are level 65 and dripping Uber gear does not make you a leader. Tactics and interpersonal skills do that! Leadership is too huge a topic to discuss here, but some pointers:
<br />

<br />
Be realistic in your objective, in relation to what classes you have, and how well you know them. If you have a badly balanced pickup group, then don't choose a difficult mission. You are setting yourself up for failure. Yes, everyone would like to be in a perfectly balanced group of proven friends, but I feel you need to be prepared to go with what you've got, adjusting the task you choose to meet the groups ability. Better to get a few points, than to fail to get lots.
<br />

<br />
For organising your group, you need not just allocate roles, but also have a buff plan. I see a lot of mana wasted by people casting buffs that don't stack, or aren't appropriate ((and yes, I admit, it is often me doing the wasting!)). In a perfect world, everyone would know everyone elses buffs inside out, but being realistic this isn't going to happen. I've now made up some socials that describe the effects of my buffs, and ask people if they have anything better, or if they want any of mine. I then spell out exactly which buffs I am going to maintain on which people. As a ranger specific tip for the less experienced, take the time to look at druid buffs. As the two classes share a lot of spell lines, the potential for wasting mana is high when a ranger is grouped with a similar level druid.
<br />

<br />
Do your organisation before starting the timer. For best result, a group should be totally organised before getting the adventure. Don't rely on using the 30 minutes to do your organisation. The best thing to do is form your group, organise it, THEN get the adventure, move to the entrance AS A GROUP, particularly if you are young enough that the zone represents a threat, then when you arrive at the entrance its immediately into buffing, re-med followed by entry. If you sit around the entrance you can bet sooner or later someone will train you a mob. A temporary LD or RL interuption can also mess up waiting till then, and if you are all ready  with 25 minutes of entry time remaining, so much the better.
<br />

<br />
Once you enter, take a few seconds to give everyone a chance to get orientated and cast any zonal spells (pets etc). I strongly suggest going with automap ON, and taking 15 seconds to add a label saying ENTRANCE in big letters! Then minimise, not close, the map window.
<br />

<br />
Then get going. However, take the time for frequent SHORT breaks. Your mana regen rate is essentially fixed (unless someone has an unreplaceable buff that is about to time out). I just don't see the point in pushing on till everyone is OOM, and then having a long break. That way if you have a bad pull there is nothing in reserve. As far as I can see, it makes more sense to med a little and often, which also gives small time windows for topping up short duration buffs, and fine tuning tactics. This requires positive control by the leader, getting people to report their mana condition regularly so you know when to rest, and when to start again, where possible getting people with higher mana to prop up those with lower. E.G. ranger top up healing can really help if the CLR is struggling. Finally make sure your lull/pull team don't restart until you are ready, and everyone is aware pulling is recommencing.
<br />

<br />
If things aren't going well:
<br />

<br />
Stop pulls. Whatever the time pressure, stop. Figure out if the problem can be fixed. Take as long as it takes to organise that. Resist the presure to go off half cocked again.
<br />

<br />
If the problem can't be fixed, essentially if you realise that the mission is too tough for the capabilities of your group, then you need to be realistic, and get what you can out of the dungeon instead of rushing on blindly with everyone OOM and buffs fading to a Total Wipe Out. Grab XP and loot instead.
<br />

<br />
I strongly recommend against (in assasination missions) lulling your way to the target  through multiple uncleared rooms. Think about it, if your group was too weak to get there in reasonable time, the odds are you will struggle to win the fight, and will want a clear escape route.
<br />

<br />
For myself, I prefer to avoid deaths. Yes, ok, you can rez back most of the lost XP, but not what you could have earned in the time wasted doing the rez itself. Its not like a dungeon is a raid for an epic piece that you've spent weeks organising the folks to show up for, though I appreciate others may feel differently on that point. Yes, sometime people die when pulls go bad, whatever the starting condition, but that is different to pushing a bad position.
<br />

<br />
Finally, the completing an LDON is all about being willing to be flexible, and using all the groups abilities to the maximum efficiency. If you've done 10 dungeons successfully, doing X,Y,Z every time, that doesn't mean that the next groups make up might be a bit different and you might need to modify your individual actions. You need to be flexible, and responsive to the other group members, polite in suggesting changes, and non defensive if someone suggests you do something different.
<br />

<br />
Hmm, bit long for a first post!<br />_________________<br />Kimble Meareheath
<br />
Clan Of Brothers
<br />
Firiona Vie Server</span><span class="gentblsmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
